#e name itself is thought to be derived from the Middle High German

carried with it not just a lineage, but an entire way of life tied to farming

Similarly, the Becker namecommon in Germanyhas its own historical  
signi!cance, often associated with the occupation of a baker or someone  
who worked with grain, bread, and food production, further underscoring  
how surnames often re"ect professions or trades vital to the survival of the  
community. It derives from the Middle High German word becker or  
the Old High German backo, both meaning baker, suggesting that my

have referred to individuals associated with millstones or communal bake

and survival of their societies.  
While we often think of family names as simply markers of heritage, they

While my DNA-derived roots stretch back thousands of years long before  
Germany became a uni!ed country, my more recent ancestors settled in  
three speci!c German regions: Bavaria, Baden, and Rhineland as well as the

economic opportunities, political unrest, and social changes.  
My personal narrative begins with ten of my great-great-grandparents and  
four of my great-grandparents, who, over a 40 year period between 1844  
and 1885, embarked on a transatlantic journey in search of a fresh start.  
Drawn by the promise of land and opportunity under the Homestead  
Act of 1862, they settled in Minnesota, primarily Otsego, Frankfort, and  
Hassan Townships. Escaping economic hardship and seeking a better life,  
these ancestors were part of a larger 19th-century migration. #is wave of  
transatlantic migration marks the beginning of my contemporary family  
tree which spans !ve generations. Referring to the earlier family tree chart,  
the light blue boxes represent ancestors who did not immigrate to the U.S.,  
the dark blue boxes are those who did immigrate, and the red boxes are  
those born in the U.S.  
#e Heuring side of my family migrated in the 1840s and 1860s, seeking  
new opportunities in the United States, while the Becker side, with one  
notable exceptionthe Barthel family, who arrived in 1856emigrated

economic, social, and political factors that motivated these families to leave  
their homelands in search of better opportunities in America.

My great-great-grandfather, Andreas Heuring, was among those who left  
Germany in search of new opportunities in America. In 1867, he immigrated  
from Bavaria, Germany to the United States, settling in Minnesota where  
he purchased an 80-acre farm in Otsego Township. He was accompanied  
on this journey by his family including his son and my great-grandfather,  
George David, who would later acquire the farm. George David had a  
new brick farmhouse built on that farm in the late 1880s; it still exists  
today. He was evidently a prominent resident in the area, as he served on  
local governing committees and was featured on a plaque commemorating  
a bridge across the Mississippi River in Elk River, highlighting his local  
political signi!cance.  
My grandfather, Alphonse Heuring, was born and grew up on that same  
family farm. He had 11 other siblings but sadly three passed away at a young  
age, two from scarlet fever when they were eight or nine and a third when  
he was only six months old, re"ecting the harsh reality of life in those times.  
A year before marrying Veronica Dehmer, Alphonse purchased a farm near  
Albertville, Minnesota, on County Road 19 in November 1912, where they  
would raise their six children. It was on this farm that my father, Norman  
Heuring, grew up alongside his !ve siblings: two older sisters, Marie and  
Lucille; two older brothers, Guido and Leander; and a younger brother,

My childhood home, just a few minutes walk from the schools and church,

Although St. Michael has since become more integrated into broader

Growing up with German roots in a small town surrounded by a farming

While my small-town environment provided stability and a solid foundation,

where things were familiar and safe, but it was also narrow in scope. As I

Living and experiencing life in such diverse regions exposed me to new
